Scenes in Play Order
Scene: The Road — New Travelers
Function: Introduce the new players. Get them comfortable in the cart, in the group, and in the world before any problems arrive.
Location: The road south of Windhelm. Bjorn's cart, moving. Cold, flat landscape. Maybe an hour out from the city.
Read Aloud
"You have all been traveling together for a few days now. You're in the back of Bjorn's cart — it's cramped, it smells like old furs and road dust, but it's warmer than walking. The road has been quiet.
Bjorn slows the cart to a stop. There's some conversation outside — muffled through the canvas. Then Bjorn opens the back flap.
'Make some room. We've picked up a few new travelers. I'm sure you'll get along.'"
Allow the new players to introduce themselves. Start with race and name. Let them describe what the group sees. Let the veteran players respond in character. Give this five to ten minutes of unstructured conversation — people settling in, getting comfortable, the social texture of strangers in a cart.
What the new players notice in the cart:
There is a figure in the back corner, wrapped in heavy furs and cloth. It does not move. It does not speak. It radiates a cold that has nothing to do with the weather — like sitting next to an open root cellar. The veteran players do not acknowledge this figure or explain it unless the new players ask.
If the new players ask about the figure:
The veteran players decide what to say. This is their problem to manage. Do not intervene.
If they explain honestly: the new players now know they're traveling with a dead woman. Good luck.
If they deflect: the new players know something is off but not what. The cold from the corner of the cart doesn't stop.
If nobody asks: that's fine too. The figure is present. It will become relevant shortly.
Exit → The cart continues toward Windhelm. Scene: The Road — The Problem.

Scene: The Road — The Problem
Function: Before the party reaches the gate, Bjorn forces the conversation about Ismara. The city is visible. The guards are visible. The problem needs solving now.
Location: The road, half a mile from Windhelm's bridge. Bjorn has stopped the cart.
Read Aloud
"Windhelm rises from the frozen landscape ahead — dark stone, Stormcloak blue on the towers, coal smoke on the wind. You can see the bridge and the gate checkpoint from here. Two guards.
Bjorn stops the cart. He turns around in his seat and looks at all of you — then at the wrapped figure in the back corner. He doesn't say anything for a moment. Then:"
"So. That's Windhelm. Guards at the gate, and they check what comes through."
He looks at Ismara. Looks back at the party.
"I've been through those gates a hundred times. They know my face. But they don't know hers, and she's —" He pauses. "Not easy to explain."
He waits. He is not going to solve this for them.
What needs to happen here: The party has to decide what to do with Ismara before they reach the checkpoint. This is a planning scene — let them talk it out. The new players are present for this conversation. How the veteran players handle it — how much they reveal, how casually they discuss hiding an undead woman — tells the new players everything they need to know about what kind of group they've joined.
If the party asks Bjorn for suggestions: "Could bury her under the cargo. Under enough furs, in the dark — maybe. Your call." He is a resource, not a decision-maker.
If the party asks Ismara: She produces a note. "I can wait." She is patient. She has waited four thousand years.
Before the party splits up, Bjorn tells the Khajiit: "If those hands are still giving you trouble, there's a temple inside the walls. Priests of Arkay — though everyone calls it the Temple of Talos these days. They'll sort you out."
Exit → The party has a plan (or doesn't). They approach the gate. Scene: The Gate.

Scene: The Gate
Function: Hrolf recognizes them. They execute their plan for Ismara. They enter the city.
Location: The bridge checkpoint. Two guards.
Read Aloud
"As your cart approaches the bridge, the younger guard straightens and squints at you. His eyes go wide.
'Wait — I know you. You're the ones from Winterhold! My cousin serves in Jarl Korir's guard. He wrote about you. You cleared that barrow — the Pale Lady business!' He's grinning. The older guard looks skeptical but interested.
Improvise from: Wind off the river. Khajiit caravan to the south. Hrolf's enthusiasm — he's a young man who has just recognized heroes from a letter his cousin sent.
What's in This Room
Guard Hrolf (Hugo): Young Nord, eager, knows who they are. Starstruck. He'll wave them through. He's the link between their reputation and the coming job — he'll be present when the first victim arrives and will vouch for them.
The Older Guard: Veteran, bored. "Frostmere, eh? Keep your weapons sheathed inside." Doesn't obstruct Hrolf.
Hrolf (Hugo)'s attention: He is looking right at the cart. He wants to see everything the heroes have. Whatever plan the party made in the previous scene, they execute it now under Hrolf (Hugo)'s enthusiastic gaze. If they're hiding Ismara, Hrolf (Hugo)'s nosiness is the obstacle. If they're leaving her outside, his attention is on them, not the cart.
The Moves: Getting In
Option A: Leave Ismara outside with the Khajiit → Works. What they did last time. Hrolf doesn't question it — Khajiit caravans camp outside all the time.
Option B: Hide Ismara in the cart → Guile (Standard) to keep Hrolf (Hugo) distracted while Bjorn drives through. Hrolf (Hugo) is chatty and distractible.
Success: Through. Hrolf (Hugo) waves the cart past.
Failure: Hrolf (Hugo) asks "What's in the cart? Can I see?" He's not suspicious — excited and nosy. Hard Guile (-2) or a firm "It's cargo, lad."
Option C: Something else → Set difficulty. Let them try.
Exit → Order of Business, then The Hook.
Living World Note — Stormcloak Intelligence: Hrolf (Hugo) just announced the party's identity loudly at the gate. Ulfric's agents are everywhere in Windhelm — they are in the middle of a careful intelligence operation, gauging support across every hold. A group of armed outsiders who cleared a barrow in Winterhold and are now arriving with a heavily-wrapped silent companion will be noted. Not acted on. Noted. If the party ever feels watched in Candlehearth Hall, this is why. It produces nothing in Adventure 1. It's background that exists whether or not the players find it.

