The Order of Business
Run the Seize the Day roll. Each player gets 10-20 minutes.
The Khajiit → Rotjoint Treatment
Location: The Temple of Arkay (everyone in Windhelm calls it the Temple of Talos — the priests insist it's Arkay's temple and that Talos is worshipped here alongside all the other Divines, but nobody listens). Helgrid is a priest of Arkay and a trained healer. She splits her time between the temple and the Hall of the Dead.
Helgrid examines the Khajiit's hands. She's thorough. She asks when it started, whether the pain is constant, whether the swelling responds to warmth. Then she goes quiet.
"The scarring is ahead of the inflammation. That's backwards."
She picks up the hand again, turns it.
"Rotjoint spreads outward from the joint capsule. This started somewhere else and the joint reacted to it. Like the pattern was already there and the tissue —"
She sets the hand down.
"I can manage the pain. The source is beyond what I can do here. A Master Restoration mage, maybe. The College."
She writes a formula on a scrap of parchment. "Quintus Navale, Gray Quarter. He'll compound this. Come back if it changes."
Cost: 20g for Helgrid's examination and initial poultice. 50g for a two-week salve supply from Quintus. Effect: Penalty reduced from -2 to -1 Agility TN with salve.
[GM note: She noticed something. She doesn't know what. She's not going to speculate to a patient about something she can't explain — she's a professional. The observation is present. It is not flagged. Do not have Helgrid say anything else about the scarring unless directly pressed, and even then: "I don't know. That's the honest answer."]
GM Note: The Khajiit is already at the temple when the first Pale Fever victim arrives. This is not a coincidence you need to engineer — it's the natural result of them seeking treatment. The Hook flows directly from this scene.
The Orc → Suvaris Atheron
Location: An alley off the main Gray Quarter street. A Dunmer woman, older, sitting against the wall with a cloth bundle in her lap. She pulls it close when she hears someone coming.
If the Orc is loud or direct, she hides the bundle behind her and says nothing. If they're quiet, or if they sit down:
"It's from the Hall. The ones they prepare." She doesn't look up. "I take a little. At night. I know what you're going to say."
Beat.
"It tastes cold. Not — not cold like meat is cold. Cold like." She stops. "Old."
She finally looks up.
"I can hear something when I do it. Not words."
She stops there. Looks back at the bundle.
[GM note: Do not narrate the Orc's response. Do not tell the player what their character feels. Set the scene and stop. Whatever the Orc does with this is the Namira thread beginning or not beginning. Follow their lead.]
Living World Note — The Gray Quarter Network: The Gray Quarter is not just a ghetto. It's a community that has been in Windhelm for two generations and has stopped waiting for Nord goodwill. Underneath Brunwulf's visible advocacy is a quieter network — Dunmer who move information between the Quarter, the docks, and the Argonian workers outside the walls. They know things about Windhelm's underside that nobody in the Palace of Kings knows. Suvaris is part of this community. If other players talk to Dunmer beyond her, they'll hear that the Quarter has been watching strange things for weeks — not the Pale Fever (which hasn't started yet) but the general awareness of a neighborhood used to being ignored that has developed its own ways of paying attention. This isn't a new scene. It's depth behind the scenes you already have.
Players 3-6 → NPC Connections
Brunwulf Free-Winter: Decent retired veteran. Good anchor.
Calixto Vividius: Approaches the party. Warm, curious, charming. Asks about Frostmere. He is the villain. He's gathering intelligence. Play him as genuinely likeable. Do not telegraph menace.
Stormcloak Recruiter: Political texture.
Gray Quarter Merchant: Dunmer being harassed. Intervention earns trust.

Scene: The Hook
Function: The quest begins. The first Pale Fever victim arrives at the temple while Helgrid is examining the Khajiit.
Location: The Temple of Arkay.
Read Aloud
"Helgrid is mid-examination when the heavy door slams open.
Guard Hrolf (Hugo) stumbles in supporting a dockworker twice his size. The man's arm is bare despite the cold, and on his skin — geometric markings, angular and precise, emerging from within rather than drawn on. Blue-white. Faintly luminous.
Helgrid looks at the dockworker's arm. Then at the Khajiit's hands, still on the examination table. Back to the arm.
She doesn't say anything for a moment. Then: 'Get Jorleif.'"
Improvise from: The dockworker's eyes are open. He's conscious. He can't speak clearly. The marks don't hurt — he keeps saying that, confused, like he expected them to. Helgrid is examining both the Khajiit's scarring and the dockworker's marks, going back and forth. She is not speaking because she is working. When she does speak, it's clipped.
Helgrid After the Read-Aloud
She examines the dockworker in silence for two minutes. Then, to whoever is closest:
"The geometry is the same."
She means the dockworker's marks and the Khajiit's scarring. She doesn't elaborate. She looks at the marks again.
"These aren't applied. They're coming from inside the tissue. I've never —"
She stops. Looks at the Khajiit's hands again.
"Get Jorleif. Now."
If Asked About...
Response
The markings
"From inside. Not drawn on, not tattooed, not — from inside." She doesn't finish.
The catacombs
"I also tend the Hall of the Dead. There are tunnels beneath it. Old. I've been hearing sounds for weeks — grinding. I reported it." She doesn't say nobody came. Her face says it.
The disappearances
"Three people. Gravedigger. A beggar. A drifter who'd been sleeping near the Hall. Maybe a month."
Payment
"I can't. But Jorleif can."

Jorleif Arrives
He reads the room fast.
"Hrolf (Hugo) says you handled the Frostmere situation." He looks at the dockworker. At the marks. "That was an undead problem in ancient ruins."
He looks at Helgrid.
"I have disappearances near the Hall of the Dead — which is sitting on ancient ruins."
Beat.
"Tell me that's a coincidence."
They have to confirm credentials. They have to lie about Frostmere, or at least not correct whatever Korir's report said.
If they accept: "Eight hundred gold for results. Find out what's in those catacombs. Find the missing people. Stop whatever is causing this."
✓ Quest Accepted: 800g.
Living World Note — The City's Misinterpretation: When the Pale Fever spreads to Day 2 and Day 3, Windhelm's official response will be to treat it as a disease originating from the Gray Quarter. This is wrong and reflects existing prejudice rather than evidence — the Fever shows no preference for Dunmer. But the quarantine talk on Day 3, if the party is still in the city, will be aimed at the wrong neighborhood. The party walks into a city that is already misinterpreting its own crisis. If they have left by then, this continues without them — the quarantine is eventually enforced against the Gray Quarter. Brunwulf's position becomes more difficult. The dock network starts moving information about the frozen people along its existing channels.
Exit → Investigation (optional) or straight into the dungeon.

Scene: The Investigation (Optional)
Calixto (about the marks): "Geometric marks? Fascinating — and troubling. Structural notation. If someone is using that on living people... The catacombs beneath the Hall are Atmoran construction. If the source is down there, it would make sense." He's directing them to the catacombs where his own work is. He believes his work is righteous.
Wulfgar (at the Palace): Translates marks as structural anchoring notation. "Load-bearing walls in something."
Brunwulf (about disappearances): "The gravedigger vanished three weeks ago. Then a beggar. Then a drifter. All near the Hall. The guard doesn't care."

Scene: Day 2 Morning — Hrolf's Walking Tour of Horror
Function: Transition from investigation to dungeon. Hrolf (Hugo) walks the party through what happened overnight.
Location: Starts at the cart. Moves through the city.
Hrolf (Hugo) at the Cart
Hrolf (Hugo) arrives early. He hasn't slept. He doesn't sit down. "I need you to come with me." He shares, if asked: "Four more overnight. Same marks. Galmar talking about closing the Gray Quarter gates. He doesn't know what else to do."
Stop 1: The Temple — The Dunmer Victim
Hrolf (Hugo) brings them to the temple first. The Dunmer dockworker from yesterday is now worse. His eyes are open. They were brown yesterday. Now they're pale blue-white, the irises crystallized into something that catches the light like cut glass. Beautiful. Wrong. He is no longer moving. His chest rises so slowly you have to watch for ten seconds to see it. His crystalline eyes track Helgrid as she moves around the table. Helgrid confirms, "Whatever this is, it's not killing him. It's —"
Stop 2: The Hall of the Dead — Calixto's Progression
Hrolf (Hugo) leads them to the Hall of the Dead to see Calixto's latest victim. Helgrid pulls back the shroud on the latest victim, found last night at the base of the Hall's exterior steps. The notation is elaborate — covering both arms and the chest in dense geometric patterns. The organs have partially crystallized but the body didn't rupture, didn't shatter. It just... stopped. Almost like the Dunmer at the temple. But the marks are ruptured, messy, hand-carved from outside. Cut into the skin. Not emerging from within. Helgrid, looking at the previous victims next to him: "Whoever did this is getting better at it."
Stop 3: Quintus's Shop
The party goes on their own initiative. Quintus opens the door, looking exhausted. The Khajiit is standing fully crystallized. He is fully crystalline. His fur has taken on a faint blue-white sheen. He is beautiful and terrible and completely still. If they try to move the Khajiit dockworker: He cannot be moved. He is completely immovable, as if he has been physically 'anchored' to the foundation of the building.
Scene: Ismara's Apology Note
Ismara approaches the Khajiit player privately and hands them a written note. The note should be simple and direct: 'The infection was not my intention. I am sorry for the pain.' She does not wait for a response.
After the Walk — The Decision
The party has seen everything. Three threads point at the catacombs: the disappearances, the sounds Helgrid reported, and the missing gravedigger.
Ismara, if she's with them (or when they return to the cart):
She has been waiting. When the Khajiit returns, Ismara holds out a note:
"I would like to see what is beneath this city. Will you take me?"
If they say yes: she goes with them. See Ismara behavior notes in the dungeon sections below.
If they say no or later: she goes on her own. They will find her already inside — most likely in the ancient ritual chamber (Node 1, Section 2).
If nobody returns to check on her: she's already there when they arrive.

Ismara in the Catacombs — Behavior Notes
These notes apply throughout the dungeon. Reference them as needed in each section.
If the party brings her (Path A):
She walks with them. She does not automatically navigate — four thousand years have passed and things may have shifted. But she is present, engaged, and responsive.
In the upper catacombs, she touches the walls as she walks. Runs her fingers along the fitted stone. She is reading them the way you'd read a familiar book in a new edition.
If the Khajiit walks beside her, she writes: "I knew people who laid these stones."
If asked about the architecture: "This was a hall. Not a tomb. People lived here." She looks around. "The ceiling was painted."
She is not sad. She is remembering. She is standing somewhere she recognizes for the first time in four thousand years.
In the maze (Section 2):
The wards affect Ismara differently. Where the party experiences vertigo and disorientation, she experiences something more like recognition. The wards were built using principles she developed. They scramble her perception the same way, but she understands WHY, which gives her an advantage if the party thinks to ask.
If they ask her for help navigating: She examines the nearest wall. Writes: "The notation cycles. Move between pulses."
If they ask about the wards: "Defense. Against intruders." A pause. Then, with what might be pride: "It still works."
In Calixto's Workshop (Section 3):
She examines the notation on the vellum sheets. Picks one up. Looks at it the way a musician looks at sheet music transcribed by someone who can't read notes. Sets it down.
If asked what she thinks: "He is copying. Poorly."
If asked about the figure on the slab: She examines it briefly. Writes: "The substrate is wrong. The binding requires —" She stops writing. Crosses it out with a single line. Writes instead: "It would not have worked."
[GM note: She almost explained how to do it correctly. She caught herself. The crossed-out line is visible to the Khajiit if they're watching. She chose not to teach them. File this.]
She does not touch Viola or the slab figure. Her interest in Calixto's work is academic and dismissive.
In the Boss Fight (Section 4):
When Calixto sees Ismara, he sees a Draugr in ancient armor. Dangerous. He directs the Guardian at her first.
Ismara does not fight unless the party is losing. She positions herself near a wall, out of the main combat, and watches.
If the party is losing badly (multiple characters down): Ismara acts. She raises a hand and a wall of black ice rises between the Guardian and the party — buying them a round to regroup. First time they see her use magic. She does not explain.
If Calixto speaks his "bring her back" line while Ismara is present: She watches him. She does not react visibly. But the Khajiit, if watching her, might notice her hand tighten on her notebook.
[GM note: Calixto is trying to resurrect someone using a bastardized version of a technique Ismara invented. He is doing it badly and killing people. Ismara's reaction is not anger — it's something she can't fully express through a Draugr body. Recognition. Something adjacent to pity.] pick up here.
If the party doesn't bring her (Path B):
They find her in the maze — most likely Node 1. She went on her own.
"You hear scratching before you see her. Not Draugr scratching — deliberate, rhythmic, like someone writing quickly.
Ismara is sitting on the floor of the chamber, her back against the base of one of the seven frozen figures. Her notebook is open across her knees and she is writing with a speed and focus you haven't seen from her before. Pages of notation — dense, geometric, filling every margin.
The frozen figures tower above her. She is sitting among them like someone who has come home to a house full of old photographs.
She looks up when you arrive. She holds up the notebook — a page covered in annotations, comparisons, arrows connecting her notation to the figures' skin. She is excited. This is the most animated you have ever seen her."
If the Khajiit is present, she writes: "Look at this. Look at what they built."
She wants to show them. She wants to share this.

The Journey — Descent into the Catacombs
Read Aloud
"Helgrid's key turns in the lock with a sound like a bone breaking. Cold air rushes up — not Windhelm cold. Older cold. The stairs descend into fitted stone corridors: precise Atmoran blocks joined without mortar, burial alcoves lining both walls.
Most alcoves are sealed. But as you descend: fresh boot prints in the dust. Someone has been here recently. And often. The prints lead deeper."
Clues: Guile (Standard) — one person, medium build, soft-soled shoes. Heavy loads in, light loads out. Faint smell of embalming fluid and bone meal.

The Dungeon: The Windhelm Catacombs
Environmental Effect: 1 FP per hour. Ancient cold from the Atmoran stone. Track time.

Section 1: The Guardian
Function: First combat. Something has disturbed the dead down here.
Read Aloud
"The corridor opens into a burial chamber. Four alcoves are shattered open from the inside. The boot prints cut straight through without stopping — whoever walks these halls isn't bothered by what's in here.
Two figures stand motionless in the far corner. Ancient Nords, desiccated, rusted armor, blue-burning eyes. Frost crawls from their feet. They turn toward your light."
Interactive elements: Broken alcoves (cover, +2 DR from ranged), frost on floor (difficult terrain), boot prints (Calixto walks past with a control amulet).
