Section 2: The Puzzle — The Atmoran Confusion Ward
Function: Psychic maze. The corridors are fixed. The party's perception isn't. 5-minute real-time timer.
Read Aloud
"The corridor widens into a network of passages — all identical. Atmoran notation covers every wall. The torchlight catches the carvings and for a moment the geometric patterns seem to move, rearranging in the corner of your vision.
You blink. The corridor ahead looks exactly like the one you just came from. Something about this place is wrong in a way you can't articulate."
How to Run the Maze
Step 1: Set a 5-minute timer on your phone. Put it on the table. When asked: "You'll see."
Step 2: Use a 9-node schematic drawn on a notecard (keep hidden):
1 --- 2 --- 3
|           |
4     5     6
|           |
7 --- 8 --- 9

Connections: 1-2, 2-3, 1-4, 3-6, 4-7, 6-9, 7-8, 8-9, 2-5, 5-8
Key locations:
Node 8: boss room
Node 5: Calixto's workshop door (the goal)
Node 4: Ancient ritual chamber (seven frozen figures, ice-crowned woman panel)
Node 3: Calixto's supply cache (his map solves the maze)
Node 7: Namira chamber (Orc content)
Node 9: Draugr patrol (2 Frost Draugr, avoidable)
Nodes 2, 1, 6: Empty corridors. Atmosphere only.
Step 3: Every 5 minutes, rotate the schematic 90° clockwise. Nodes don't change — relative positions do from the party's perspective. They say "north," you interpret based on current orientation.
Step 4 — Sensory Cue: Each rotation: "A wave of vertigo — brief but intense. The torchlight flickers. The corridor ahead looks unfamiliar, as if you've never seen it. Then it passes. But something has changed."
What the Party Can Do
Figure out the pattern: If they connect vertigo to the 5-minute intervals. Magic (Standard) confirms: "The wards pulse on a cycle. Your perception shifts, not the corridors." Once they know, they can plan moves between pulses.
Resist magically: Magic (Hard -2) suppresses the effect on one person for 10 minutes (two cycles). They guide the group.
Find Calixto's map (Node 3): Solves the maze completely.
Brute force: Try every direction. Works but costs time (FP drain) and risks encounters.
Node Contents
Node 4 — The Ancient Ritual Chamber:
Seven figures stand in the chamber. Not burial positions — standing, upright, spaced with mathematical precision. Ancient Nords in ceremonial dress, not armor. Their skin is covered in geometric notation — the same system as the Pale Fever marks, as the Khajiit's scarring, as the crude copies in Calixto's workshop. But these are older, more elaborate, and written with a fluency that makes even Wulfgar's best translations look like a child's primer.
They are dead. Long dead. Unlike the crystallized victims in the city above, these figures' eyes are closed. Whatever process was meant to happen here was interrupted before completion. They froze mid-ritual. They have been standing here ever since.
The notation on their skin, if anyone examines it closely (Guile Standard or anyone who has worked with Wulfgar): Each figure's marks are different — different positions in a larger pattern. If mapped, the seven positions form a geometric structure that uses the same spatial logic as the Pale Fever victims' positions in the city above. Same system. Much older. Smaller scale.
A carved panel on the far wall shows a crowned figure at the center of lines radiating outward in every direction. The lines connect to smaller figures at their ends. Architectural notation borders it. The carving is stylized Atmoran work, worn by four thousand years.
[GM note: Describe this as a diagram. A system. Something technical. Don't name the figure. Don't specify "ice crown" — it's stylized, worn. A crown shape is present. The party is looking at a fragment of the original ritual schematic carved by practitioners of Ismara's discipline.]
If Ismara is present (either path):
She moves among the figures slowly. She touches one's face. She examines the notation on its skin — traces a line with her finger the way you'd trace a line of handwriting you recognize.
She is quiet for a long time.
If the Khajiit asks what she's looking at, or what she's thinking, she writes:
"They were practicing what I taught. A smaller version. It should have worked at this scale."
She looks at the figures again. Touches the one nearest to her on the shoulder.
"Something interrupted them before they could finish."
She knows what interrupted them. The Dragon Cult sealed this place the same way they sealed her. She does not say this. She touches the frozen figure's shoulder one more time and moves on.
[GM note: She is mourning. Not dramatically. But she is standing in a room with seven people who tried to continue her work after she was imprisoned and were stopped and frozen here as a consequence. She taught principles. They tried to practice them. She has been frozen upstairs while they were frozen downstairs. Let the Khajiit player see this. Let them see her being a person, not an intellect.]
Node 3 — Calixto's Supply Cache: Map (solves maze), ~50g/player, Scroll of Flame Cloak, 3× Minor Healing.
Node 7 — Namira Chamber: Sealed room past a collapse. A body, not decomposed, hands folded. Symbol on the floor — not Atmoran, not Nordic. Older. The Orc feels something. Describe the room only. If they touch the body: settling warmth. If moved: it decomposes within hours.
Node 9 — Draugr Patrol: 2 Frost Draugr (same stats as Section 1 above). Avoidable (Agility Standard stealth) or fought. The timer doesn't pause for combat.
Random Encounter (after 25 min): A Frost Draugr emerges in the party's current node. Communicates: keep moving.
