Section 3: The Setback — Calixto's Workshop
Function: Reveal Calixto's work. Find victims. The setback: Calixto has fled deeper, collapsing the passage behind him.
Read Aloud
"The door opens into a space that makes your stomach turn.
Worktables covered in alchemical equipment — retorts, alembics, soul gem fragments, jars of organs. Ritual circles in chalk and blood. Atmoran notation copied badly onto vellum, annotated in frantic Common handwriting.
Two alcoves modified into cells. One holds a woman — alive, gagged, terrified, geometric marks carved into her arms by hand. Not from within like the dockworker's. Cut with a knife. The other cell is empty. Dark stains.
On a stone slab: a figure no longer fully human. Stitched, augmented, covered in messy, ruptured carved notation. Not moving. The notation is precise, almost surgical, but still hand-carved from outside, not emerging from within. Calixto's best work. Still not good enough.
A journal lies open. The handwriting is Calixto's.
Behind the slab, a passage leads deeper. Fresh rubble blocks it — collapsed deliberately. Footsteps retreating on the other side. Running."
Key Details
Viola Giordano (prisoner): Alive. Confirms Calixto. "The museum man. He did this." Her hand-cut marks are visually similar to but distinctly different from the Pale Fever's organic marks. A clue the party won't understand yet.
The Figure on the Slab: Assembled body. His most refined attempt — the notation is precise, almost surgical, recognizably close to the marks on the Pale Fever victims. Almost. But hand-carved from outside, not emerging from within. Calixto's best work. Still not good enough.
Calixto's Progression — Visible in the Workshop:
On the worktables: vellum sheets pinned in chronological order. Early sheets show crude notation — big, imprecise, with frustrated annotations in the margins: "Wrong. Wrong. WHY wrong." Later sheets show finer work, smaller notation, fewer margin notes. The most recent sheet is almost clean — the notation is precise, careful. Almost.
Preserved samples in jars: sections of skin with notation carved into them, preserved in alchemical fluid. Early samples show ragged cuts, torn tissue. Later samples show cleaner incisions, more precise geometry. He has been saving his practice work.
The Missing Gravedigger:
If the party reaches the workshop on Day 2 (before Night 3): The missing gravedigger is in the second cell. Alive. Gagged. Marks partially carved into his arms — Calixto started working on him last night but didn't finish. He is terrified. He can be freed the same way as Viola (Agility Standard or Might Standard on the lock). His wife filed the missing person report at the temple that morning. Returning him to her is the resolution of that thread.
If the party reaches the workshop on Day 3 (after Night 3 — see contingency below): The gravedigger is on the slab. Crystallized — Calixto's first passable success. The cell holds a new victim.
Calixto's Journal — Key Entries:
"Week 1: The preservation matrices in the lower chamber are extraordinary. Those seven figures are still intact after millennia. If the substrate can maintain consciousness for that duration —"
"Week 2: The notation is more complex than I realized. I can copy the shapes but the underlying logic escapes me. I need more subjects. The technique requires precision I haven't achieved yet."
"Week 3: Subject 2 is gone. The notation doesn't tolerate imprecision — or rather, it does something with it that I wasn't expecting. I have to be more careful."
"[Recent — no date:] Something has changed in the last two days. The wards have intensified dramatically. I don't know the cause — it's not my work. Something is resonating with the foundation stones. From outside, I think. Whatever it is, it's making everything unstable. I need to accelerate."
"[Final entry:] Visitors today. They had marks — the real marks, not mine. The Khajiit especially. The notation on her joints is fluent. Accent marks I've never seen. Someone who actually understands the system is working in this city and I do not know who they are. The resonance from outside is stronger than ever. I must accelerate. If I can achieve one clean binding before whoever is doing this finds me, I can prove the technique works. Then it won't matter how crude my early attempts were. The result is what matters."
GM Note: "Something resonating from outside" is Ismara's arrival. The final entry confirms Calixto saw the Khajiit's marks in his shop during Session 1 and recognized them as fluent — the "real thing" versus his copies. He knows someone else is working the same system properly. He doesn't know it's Ismara. He's racing to prove his own technique works before he's found. This is in his journal for the party to find.
The Collapsed Passage: Clear rubble (Very Hard Might -4, loud) or find the side fissure (Guile Standard, quiet, Agility Standard to navigate).
