Night 3 Contingency — Calixto Succeeds
If the party does not enter the catacombs by the end of Day 2, or enters but retreats before reaching Calixto, he has one more night to work.
What happens on Night 3:
Calixto takes the missing gravedigger and performs his most refined attempt yet. For the first time, it doesn't fail catastrophically. The gravedigger does not explode. Does not rupture. Does not shatter. The notation holds. The body crystallizes — standing, eyes open, geometric marks visible on the skin.
But it is not clean. Not like Ismara's work.
The morning of Day 3:
The gravedigger is found standing in the street outside the Hall of the Dead. Crystallized. Alive — technically. Eyes open but unfocused, not tracking movement the way Ismara's victims do. The geometric marks are present but uneven — some lines thicker than others, angles slightly off, spacing inconsistent. Where Ismara's marks emerge from within the skin seamlessly, like they grew there, Calixto's look like they were pushed through from the outside and got stuck halfway. The crystallization is cloudy rather than clear — more dirty ice than cut glass.
But it is not clean. Not like Ismara's work. The crystallization is cloudy rather than clean, crystalline — more dirty ice than cut glass. The marks look like someone was guessing.
Helgrid, if she examines both side by side:
"This isn't the same. The marks on the others are precise, consistent, architectural. This one looks like someone was guessing."
[GM note: This is actually useful for the investigation. Two different quality levels means two different sources. Calixto's crude success gives them evidence that there are two separate things happening — one competent and one amateur. They still don't know who the competent one is. But they now have proof that Calixto's work and the Pale Fever are not the same hand. Whether they draw that conclusion depends on whether they're looking.]
What Calixto does after his first success:
He doesn't stop. He is elated. He goes back for another subject. The disappearances accelerate. If the party doesn't enter the catacombs by Day 4, two more people go missing. The dungeon still works exactly the same when they finally go down — Calixto is still there, still working. The missing gravedigger on the slab is just replaced by his latest acquisition.

Ismara's Background Activity
GM tracking only.
Day 1: Surveys from outside the walls. Places first node (road laborer — becomes first Pale Fever victim that evening).
Day 2: Places second node (Gray Quarter laborer).
Day 3: Places third node (beggar near the docks). Tells the Khajiit: "I have what I need here."
Living World Note — The Docks: The docks run a secondary economy that Ulfric's court officially doesn't see. Contraband, information, people moving without papers. The Argonian workers are part of this network — not criminals, just people excluded from legal structures who have built parallel ones. A dockworker disappearing into the Pale Fever doesn't trigger an immediate city response because dockworkers go missing sometimes. The system is built to not notice. This is why Ismara's first node can vanish into the phenomenon without anyone mounting an investigation until Helgrid forces the issue at the temple.
Clues present in this adventure, none flagged:
Helgrid noticing the scarring is wrong without being able to explain it
The Khajiit potentially witnessing the node placement without context
Node 1 and vault diagrams — present, architectural, uninterpreted
Calixto's journal noting something resonating from outside — cause unstated
The Fever continuing after Calixto's death — reported as fact, not framed
None of these connect. They are not supposed to connect yet. They are threads. The weaving happens later.

